This guide [[Article description::shows how to navigate info pages using the {{c|info}} command.]]

== Introduction ==

=== What is info? ===

Most users may be familiar with the {{c|man}} documentation system. While man is good with quickly looking up items, it lacks structure in linking man pages together. This is where {{c|info}} comes in. Info pages are made using the {{c|texinfo}} tools, and can link with other pages, create menus and ease navigation in general. The next section will look at how info pages are laid out.

=== Info pages layout ===

The main info pages are held in {{Path|/usr/share/info}}. Unlike the man style directory layout, {{Path|/usr/share/info}} contains what is largely a rather extensive collection of files. These files have the following format: 

{{CodeBox|title=info file format|1=
pagename.info[-node].gz
}}

<code>pagename</code> is the actual name of the page (example: <code>wget</code>). <code>[-node]</code> is an optional construct that designates another node level (generally these are referenced to by the toplevel of the info document in question). In order to save space these info pages are compressed using the gzip compression scheme by default. Configure the <var>PORTAGE_COMPRESS</var> variable in {{Path|/etc/portage/make.conf}} to choose different compression algorithms. Additional info pages can be listed with the <var>INFOPATH</var> environment variable (usually set through the various {{Path|/etc/env.d/}} files). To get started, it's important to note the {{Path|/usr/share/info/dir}} file. This special file is used when info is ran with no parameters. It contains a listing of all info pages available for users to browse. To begin looking at navigating around in info, bring it up with no arguments: 

{{Cmd|info}}

The next chapter describes how to deal with basic info navigation.

